<DocsLayout title="Roadmap">
  <h1>Roadmap</h1>
  <p>
    <code>llmrouter</code> is pre-1.0. This page is the public plan
    for what is shipped, what is being built next, and — equally
    important — what is intentionally <em>not</em> part of the
    library. The roadmap is best-effort, not a contract; dates are
    omitted on purpose because most of the work is driven by a small
    team.
  </p>
  <p>
    Versions follow <a href="https://semver.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">semantic versioning</a>.
    While we are pre-1.0, expect minor breakages between minor
    versions (v0.1 → v0.2 → v0.3). Patch versions (v0.1.0 → v0.1.1)
    will never break the API; only tests, docs, and internals change.
  </p>

  <h2 id="released">Released</h2>

  <h3 id="v0-1-1">v0.1.1 — Test hardening</h3>
  <p>
    A pure quality release. No source changes, no API changes,
    nothing for an application caller to do.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>330-subtest table-driven test suite</strong> covering
      core types, options, the streaming producer, error wrapping,
      and both providers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>100% statement coverage</strong> on the root package
      (<code>llmrouter.go</code>, <code>options.go</code>,
      <code>stream.go</code>, <code>errors.go</code>).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>90.4% statement coverage</strong> on each provider
      package — the uncovered branches are non-2xx error paths that
      need a full HTTP fixture round-trip and will land in the
      provider integration suite.
    </li>
    <li>
      No public-API changes. v0.1.0 application code runs unchanged.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0-1-0">v0.1.0 — Initial public release</h3>
  <p>The library&rsquo;s first tagged release. Includes the core surface and the first two providers.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Core API</strong>: the
      <code>Provider</code> interface, <code>ChatRequest</code> /
      <code>Message</code> / <code>Chunk</code> types, the
      <code>Stream</code> handle, the option pattern
      (<code>WithAPIKey</code>, <code>WithBaseURL</code>,
      <code>WithHTTPClient</code>, <code>WithTimeout</code>,
      <code>WithExtra</code>), and the <code>ErrUpstream</code>
      error wrapper.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>OpenAI provider</strong> with byte passthrough on
      requests and chunks, plus the <code>WithBaseURL</code> override
      that turns it into a universal OpenAI-compatible client
      (OpenRouter, Together, Groq, vLLM, Ollama, LM Studio, anything
      that speaks <code>/v1/chat/completions</code> SSE).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Anthropic provider</strong> with full bidirectional
      translation: OpenAI <code>messages</code> →
      Anthropic <code>/v1/messages</code> request body (including
      lifting the <code>system</code> role into the top-level
      <code>system</code> field), and Anthropic SSE events
      (<code>message_start</code>, <code>content_block_delta</code>,
      <code>message_delta</code>, <code>message_stop</code>) →
      OpenAI-shaped delta chunks.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Stream API</strong> with a buffered chunks channel,
      a producer goroutine, single-consumer semantics, and
      <code>context.Context</code> cancellation that propagates all
      the way to the in-flight HTTP request.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="v0-2">Planned for v0.2 — Cloud provider triple</h2>
  <p>
    Adds the three managed cloud LLM endpoints that most enterprise
    deployments end up using. Each one is a real new provider with
    its own auth scheme and its own body translation, not just a
    base-URL flip.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Azure OpenAI Service provider.</strong>
      Deployment-URL-based endpoint
      (<code>https://&lt;resource&gt;.openai.azure.com/openai/deployments/&lt;deployment&gt;/chat/completions</code>),
      <code>api-key</code> header instead of
      <code>Authorization: Bearer</code>, mandatory
      <code>api-version</code> query parameter. Request and response
      shapes are OpenAI-compatible; only the auth and URL change.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>AWS Bedrock provider.</strong> SigV4 request signing
      against
      <code>bedrock-runtime.&lt;region&gt;.amazonaws.com</code>, plus
      per-model-family body translation: Claude family
      (Anthropic-shaped <code>messages</code>), Llama family
      (Meta-shaped <code>prompt</code> + chat templating), Titan
      family (Amazon-shaped <code>inputText</code>). The model
      family is detected from the <code>Model</code> string in
      <code>ChatRequest</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Google Vertex AI provider.</strong> Application Default
      Credentials (ADC) for auth, project + region in the endpoint
      URL, Google&rsquo;s
      <code>publishers/google/models/...:streamGenerateContent</code>
      surface translated into OpenAI-shaped chunks.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>More OpenAI-compatible endpoint examples</strong> in
      the provider tests — verified round trips against the wire
      format of OpenRouter, Together, Groq, vLLM, and Ollama, so
      regressions get caught.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    v0.2 may also include small breaking changes to the
    <code>WithExtra</code> option to accommodate the per-provider
    metadata each cloud endpoint needs (Azure deployment name,
    Vertex project ID and region). We will list any such breakages
    in the changelog with migration notes.
  </p>

  <h2 id="v0-3">Planned for v0.3 — Beyond chat</h2>
  <p>
    Once the cloud triple lands, the next chunk of work is to round
    out the request and response surface with the things people
    already use via <code>Raw</code> passthrough — tools, multimodal
    content, embeddings.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Typed tool-call passthrough.</strong> Today, tool
      definitions and tool-call responses flow through via
      <code>ChatRequest.Raw</code> and <code>Chunk.Raw</code> — which
      works, but is byte-string-typed. v0.3 adds
      <code>ChatRequest.Tools []ToolDef</code> on the way out and
      <code>Choice.Delta.ToolCalls []ToolCallDelta</code> on the way
      back, normalised to OpenAI shape and translated to Anthropic
      <code>tool_use</code> / <code>tool_result</code> blocks in the
      Anthropic provider.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Multimodal content helpers.</strong> Constructors for
      image URLs (<code>llmrouter.ImageURLContent</code>) and image
      bytes (<code>llmrouter.ImageBytesContent</code>) that build
      the right content-block shape for both OpenAI and Anthropic.
      Removes the &ldquo;build the JSON yourself and stuff it in
      <code>Raw</code>&rdquo; workaround.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>First-class embeddings API.</strong> A separate
      <code>Embed(ctx, EmbedRequest) (EmbedResponse, error)</code>
      method on the <code>Provider</code> interface — kept distinct
      from <code>CompletionStream</code> because the request shape,
      response shape, and lifecycle are different (no streaming, no
      <code>Stream</code> handle).
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="v0-4">Planned for v0.4 — Audio and vision</h2>
  <p>
    Audio and vision are big enough that they deserve their own
    minor version. The plan is to bundle them rather than
    interleaving them with v0.3&rsquo;s work.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Audio / TTS / STT.</strong> OpenAI Whisper (STT),
      OpenAI GPT-4o audio (in &amp; out), Vertex audio. The shape
      will be similar to the embeddings API — separate methods on
      <code>Provider</code> with their own request and response
      types, not shoehorned into <code>CompletionStream</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Vision provider abstraction.</strong> Multimodal
      <em>output</em> (e.g. image generation) handled with its own
      typed surface. Multimodal <em>input</em> (image
      understanding) is already covered by v0.3&rsquo;s multimodal
      content helpers.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="v1-0">Planned for v1.0 — API freeze</h2>
  <p>
    Once v0.4 ships and the surface has been stable for a few
    months, v1.0 freezes the public API. The contract from v1.0
    onwards:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      No breaking changes to exported types, functions, or
      interfaces within the v1.x series.
    </li>
    <li>
      Backward-compatible additions (new options, new methods on
      <code>Provider</code> with sensible defaults, new fields on
      types) are minor bumps.
    </li>
    <li>
      Bug fixes are patch bumps.
    </li>
    <li>
      Breaking changes — if they ever happen — bump major.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Until v1.0, we do <strong>not</strong> guarantee backward
    compatibility between minor versions. Pin a minor in your
    <code>go.mod</code> and read the changelog before bumping.
  </p>

  <h2 id="out-of-scope">Out of scope — and staying that way</h2>
  <p>
    The most important part of any roadmap is what it&rsquo;s
    <em>not</em>. The following features are intentionally not in
    <code>llmrouter</code>, will not be added, and would be rejected
    in a PR. They are not bad ideas — they are the
    <em>wrong layer</em>. They belong in the gateway you build
    <em>on top of</em> a library like <code>llmrouter</code>, not
    inside the library itself. Putting them in the library forces
    them on every caller, contaminates the API surface, and traps
    operational concerns (caching, budgets, multi-tenant policy)
    inside a Go module that can never be the right home for them.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Rate limiting.</strong> Token-bucket rate limiting
      across vendors is a property of <em>your</em> deployment, not
      of the library. Build it in the HTTP handler in front of
      <code>llmrouter</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Budget caps.</strong> Per-tenant or per-key cost
      ceilings need persistent counters, an authorisation model, and
      a billing source of truth. None of that belongs in a library.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Response caching.</strong> Caching needs a cache key
      strategy (do you include the full message history? do you
      ignore <code>user</code>? do you cache by hash or by content?),
      an eviction policy, and a backing store. All of which are
      deployment decisions.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Vector store / RAG.</strong> Vector databases,
      retrievers, chunkers, rerankers, and prompt assembly are an
      entire product category. <code>llmrouter</code> will give you
      the embedding API in v0.3; the retrieval pipeline is yours to
      build.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Persistent conversation state.</strong> Storing turns
      across requests, summarising old context, paging history out
      to disk — these are application concerns. The library&rsquo;s
      <code>ChatRequest</code> is a single call; persistence lives
      one layer up.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A bundled HTTP server.</strong> <code>llmrouter</code>
      is a library, not a binary. Run it inside your own server.
      The examples in
      <a href="/llmrouter/docs/guides/chat-gateway">Build a chat
      gateway</a> show how to wrap it in a few lines of
      <code>net/http</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you want all of these in one box, the answer in the Python
    ecosystem is LiteLLM. There is no Go equivalent today, and
    <code>llmrouter</code> is deliberately not trying to become
    one. We&rsquo;d rather be the boring, byte-exact, single-purpose
    library that a gateway is built on top of.
  </p>

  <h2 id="influence">How to influence the roadmap</h2>
  <p>
    The plan above is a plan, not a promise. The most effective way
    to move something earlier is to file an issue at
    <a href="https://github.com/elloloop/llmrouter/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/elloloop/llmrouter/issues</a>
    with:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The <code>type:feature</code> label.</li>
    <li>
      A concrete use case — &ldquo;we need Vertex auth because our
      compliance team requires Google&rsquo;s key management,&rdquo;
      not &ldquo;please add more providers.&rdquo;
    </li>
    <li>The shape of the API you&rsquo;d want, if you&rsquo;ve thought about it.</li>
    <li>Whether you&rsquo;d be willing to send the PR yourself.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Issues with a real use case attached almost always move ahead
    of speculative ones, and issues with a willing contributor
    behind them move fastest of all. See
    <a href="/llmrouter/docs/project/contributing">Contributing</a>
    for how to send the PR once the issue is agreed.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
